The government has voted an important law in August 2015 that allows club to obtain a restructuration and haircut of their tax and social debt through the adhesion to the created state program PROFUT “PROGRAMA DE MODERNIZAÇÃO DA GESTÃO E DE RESPONSABILIDADE FISCAL DO FUTEBOL BRASILEIRO”.

The adhesion to this program promotes good governance practices and transparency. Clubs are obliged to comply with some requirements:

  • By laws compliant with PROFUT to include responsibilities of diretores and sanctions in case of mismanagement as well as independence of control / audit body (conselho fiscal)
  • Financial statements compliant with PROFUT accounting standards
  • Management reports including operations of anticipation of future revenues signed by diretores and conselho fiscal
  • Clubs cannot anticipate more than 30% of the revenues for the year after the mandate of the current president and must reduce its deficit to a maximum of 10% of its revenues in 2017, 2018 and 5% from 2019
  • Maximum 4-year mandate to be renewed for 1 term maximum
  • Comply with all their current tax and social obligations
  • Wages and image rights paid to players must not be more than 80% of revenues from Football activities and clubs must maintain minimum investments in academy and women’s football

As most of the clubs are in the program it has a positive consequence on the governance of Brazilian Football.

The state has no power to sanction clubs apart from excluding them from PROFUT and as a consequence having the club losing the benefits from this program.  

Since 2018, the Brazilian federation “CBF” is implementing a licencing system to promote best practices establishing several criteria clubs must comply with to be able to participate to CBF competitions:

  • Sporting
  • Infrastructures
  • Administration and human resources
  • Legal
  • Financial

The CBF can sanction clubs that would not respect such criteria and we see this trend as positive for the governance of the Brazilian Football.

The clubs signed new agreements with Globo (S&P BB+ rating) and Turner (subsidiary of Time Warner and ultimately AT&T rated BBB S&P) for the period between 2019 and 2024. This includes a new distribution system for each broadcaster.

Globo offers to clubs R$ 600 million for free TV and R$ 500 million for pay TV with the following distribution:

  • A fixed fee equivalent to 40% of the total amount that will be Reais “R$” 22 million
  • 30% of the value paid in accordance with the season final ranking
  • 30% of the value paid in accordance with the appearance on TV

Turner (only pay TV) offers to clubs R$ 500 million for pay TV with a slightly different distribution:

  • 50% as an equal share
  • 25% regarding season ranking
  • 25% in accordance with appearances on TV

Under this new system, clubs won’t benefit from parachute payments in case of relegation. Every club is free to negotiate individually contracts with broadcasters. It regards only domestic rights for the Brasileiro Série A.

On top of this clubs can sign agreements with Globo for Pay per View in which Globo offers around R$ 650 million that will be distributed as per the fan base of the club.

For the first time an agreement is being negotiated regarding international TV rights and sponsoring of Brasileiro Serie A.

It is difficult to estimate the overall value of TV money that will receive clubs even though the total value will increase with largest clubs (though pay per view) taking benefit from it while some other clubs in the middle might see their slice of TV money decrease. Smaller clubs will benefit from the equal share to increase money received from TV.

The consistently good performances of the German participants in the European Cups have led to 2nd place in the UEFA’s five-year ranking. Bundesliga (79.50) lies below Liga BBVA (104.14) but abovePremier League (75.11) and Italy (72.83). 

UEFA ranking is led by solid and regular performances in Champions League (Bayern Munich and Borussia Dortmund) and Europa League (Schalke 04 and Bayer Leverkusen).

Financial fundamentals

In term of revenue generation the Premier League clearly tops the big 5 leagues with almost double revenue than the Bundesliga which is the second largest league in term of revenue generation:

Source : DNCG, Bundesliga, CSD and Calcio reports. Premier League individual accounts aggregated by Sport Value (exchange rate 1.25 € = 1£).

 In line with revenue, Premier League spends the mosts in wages of players, staff and administration (payroll) including social security tax. Liga BBVA made significant efforts to turn toward profitability and present an adequate payroll to turnover ratio as well as Bundesliga which has historically a strong track record in cost management. Note that the difference in social security expense is significant from one country to another. Indeed French clubs will pay around 35%, English clubs around 12% Spanish, German and Italian clubs around 3-4% only.

In term of profitability, Bundesliga has a good track record of profits generation. the Premier League made after years of losses a net profit in 2013/14. The Spanish Liga BBVA thanks to strict cost control registered also a significant net profit (FC Barcelona and Real Madrid aggregated net profit is € 80 mm).Note that contrary to Ligue 1 clubs Liga BBVA and Premier League are more indebted and to generate cash has been vital to serve the debt. Série A clubs struggle with poor profitability and large indebtedness.

Source: Football Leagues – Net TV rights distributed to 1st division clubs

(*): Bundesliga 1.: 2017 – 18 estimates

Under the 2013 – 17 TV rights cycle, domestic rights amounted to € 2.51 billion for the period with an average of € 628 mm of net domestic TV rights per season plus € 150 mm of international rights. The allocation formula between Bundesliga 1 and Bundesliga 2 (Second Division) amounted to 79/21. The spread between the club ranked first and last in a so called “4 year ranking list” was 2:1 meaning that the best performing club received twice the sum which was paid to the last ranked one. “4 year ranking list” implied as well that the 3 past seasons were also taken into consideration. This system wasthe second most equitable in Europe behind Premier League (volatility of the broadcasting right revenues among clubs was 0.396 vs. 0.137 in England). 

Sky Deutschland held vitually all live television rights for the Bundesliga, while public broadcasters have rights to show extended highlights later on the day when games are played.

In 2016, Bundesliga signed a new broadcasting agreement for the 2017-21 period for a net amount of € 4.64 billion, hence a growth of 85% vs previous cycle. This growth is notably related to the "no single buyer" rule with the competition between several actors vs former monopoly of Sky Deutschland over Bundesliga TV rights:

  • Sky Deutschland will maintain its domination with 266 matches of Bundesliga 1 and the entirety of Bundesliga 2
  • Eurosport, as a new actor, will broadcast 43 matches of Bundesliga 1
  • Amazon, as a new actor, will be the first internet player to win a commercial package in a major championship

Regarding international TV rights, an agreement has already been signed with China for an amount of € 250 mm to cover the 2018 –– 2023 period. The agreement was concluded between the Deutsche Fussball Liga and Suning, a Chinese operator.

The allocation formula for domestic rights between Bundesliga 1 and Bundesliga 2 will change:

  • 70% of total TV prize will be shared between Bundesliga 1 and Bundesliga 2 clubs by taking into account sports results in both competitions over the last 5 years. In Bundesliga 1, the 1st team over the last 5 years will receive 5.8% of the 70%, the 18th team, 2.9%. In Bundesliga 2, the 1st team will receive 1.69%, the 18th, 0.75%
  • 23% of total TV prize will take into account the weighted ranking over the last 5 years of the 36 clubs playing into both competitions
  • 5% will take into account the general ranking of the 36 clubs over the last 20 years
  • 2% will take into account the use of U23 players in terms of minutes played

Regarding the allocation formula for international rights:

  • 25% will be equally shared between Bundesliga 1 clubs
  • 50% will be allocated to the teams having participated to UEFA competitions over the last 5 years on the basis of UEFA points brought to the German Football League
  • 25% will be allocated to the teams having participated to UEFA competitions over the last 5 years on the basis of the number of games played, including play-offs

Legislation and Economic Control

Clubs in the Bundesliga are subject to regulations not unlike the UEFA Financial Fair Play Regulations agreed upon in September 2009.

Financial regulation in Bundesliga has 3 pillars:

1.     Licensing System

At the end of each season, clubs in the Bundesliga must apply to the German Football Federation (DFB) for a licence to participate again the following year; only when the DFB, who have access to all transfer documents and accounts, are satisfied that there is no threat of insolvency and give its approval. 

There are three main financial conditions for approval:

  • Forecasted positive liquidity situation at the end of the upcoming season,
  • Positive net equity in the last regular balance sheet
  • Forecasted positive net equity at the end of the upcoming season

Sanctions (in case of violation of conditions and obligations) can be the following ones:

  • Temporary suspension (max. two months)
  • Points deductions
  • Monetary fines

2.     Safeguard Fund

The DFB has a safeguard fund goal in case of temporary liquidity crisis of clubs in the Bundesliga in order to safeguard match and league operations.

Financing:

  • Solidarity Volume: 10 million € per season
  • Payment: max. two-months of salaries or 5 million €
  • Consequence for the club: up to 3 points deducted
  • Reimbursement: next rate of media contracts money

3.     Ownership Rules (“50 plus 1 clause”)

Football clubs are association that must hold the majority of voting rights of the attached football company (plc., ltd., etc.):  50% + 1 voting rights in the General Assembly.

The issuing of non-voting shares remains unaffected (pure capital contributions are not restricted). Two exceptions exist: Leverkusen (Bayer AG) and Wolfsburg (Volkswagen AG) that used to be factory sporting teams before becoming solely football associations.

Bundesliga has taken over the top spot in term of attractiveness since it has renovated and expanded capacity of its stadiums for the 2006 World Cup. As a result, match day income is a more important revenue stream for Bundesliga clubs than for clubs among the Big 5 leagues (English Premier League, French Ligue 1, Italian Lega Calcio, Spanish Liga BBVA, and German Bundesliga). The Bundesliga recorded an average of 43,499 spectators at the past season’s 306 matches (average capacity utilization stood at 90%). This means that the Bundesliga remains the football league attracting the highest average turnout worldwide.

Contrary to Italy where some clubs share their grounds, every Bundesliga club has its own stadium, and most of the time, its ownership. Stadiums have a capacity of 48,332 seats in average – i.e. the biggest capacity in Europe, far above the 30,467 seats in average for the 5 main European championships. The smallest stadium is the Audi Sportpark (FC Ingolstadt – capacity 15,000), and the largest Westfalenstadion (Dortmund – capacity 81,359).

In the last 6 years in Germany and England the average attendance has slightly risen (respectively +2.2% and +2.9%), while the number has remained stable in France, whilst a decline has been recorded in Spain (-4.7%) and Italy (-6.9%).

Germany has been historically one of the major countries in Football. The records of the “Mannschaft”, the German National Team, are impressive both at the continental level and the world level. In terms of registered players, Germany is on the top spot – there were 6.3M registered players in Germany in 2006 according to FIFA, i.e. by far the biggest amount worldwide, runner up being the United States with 4.2M registered players.

According per the last UEFA benchmarking report Jupiler Pro league aggregated revenues excluding transfers of players of 383 m€ that is the 10th in Europe after England (5.3 billion €), Spain (2.8 billion €), Germany (2.8 billion €), Italy (2.2 billion €), France (1.6 billion €), Russia (813 m€), Turkey (731 m€), Netherlands (505 m€) and Portugal (431 m€).

However competitive balance is more effective than in other countries:

In Portugal the top 3 clubs account for 70% of the total revenues of the league. In Netherlands the top 3 clubs account for 55% of the revenues of the league while in Belgium the top 3 represents 33% of the revenues of the League.

UEFA

Belgium is the 8th UEFA coefficient regarding 2018/2019 trying to catch up with Portugal and being challenged by Ukraine. The trend is positive for Belgium as highlighted below:

They are outperforming vs richer leagues and can benefit from financial difficulties of Turkish and Portuguese clubs as well as the difficult political situation in Ukraine. The reform of UEFA competitions had a strong impact on these leagues as regard to club’s qualification to lucrative UEFA competitions.

National TV rights in Jupiler Pro League are worth € 80 mm per season following a 3-year cycle (2017 – 20) with a distribution to clubs after deductions of 71 m€ to clubs shared according to the following rule:

  • Article 1, equal share (fond de solidarité) : 12 m€
  • Article 2, current season ranking: 1.8 m€
  • Article 3, 5 years sports results: 1.8 m€
  • Article 4, TV appearances: 3.3 m€
  • Article 5, indemnities relegated clubs: 1.25 m€
  • Article 6, play off 1: 7.6 m€
  • Article 7, balance season and historical ranking: 41.6 m€
  • Article 8, play off 2: 3 m€
  • Article 9, Belgium trained players: 1 m€

The amount of TV rights received by Belgium clubs is low vs other leagues including direct competitors (Netherlands and Portugal) however with a better balance and equal distribution system strengthening the league: 

     Some uncertainty remains as regard to the Tv rights from 2020-2021 which are not sold yet are an object of discussion within the Jupiler pro league.

The Jupiler Pro League is not running like the other leagues in Europe. The competition is composed by 16 teams, at the end of the regular phase (30 games) clubs will attend the PO (Play-Off):

- PO1: 6 best teams of the regular phase will play against each other in home and away games. Points are divided by 2.

- PO2: Teams from 7th to 16th rank of the regular phase will play against teams from 1st  to 6th  rank  of the Proximus League (2nd division in Belgium). Clubs are divided in 4 groups of 4 teams, the first team of each group will play a knockout phase to determined PO2 winner.

The last team of the regular phase is relegated in second division.

With only 1/16 team relegated, the risk of relegation is very limited (6,25%), in comparison with other leagues like France (12,5%).

In comparison with other leagues, average attendance and stadium capacity are weak in Belgium. During 2017-2018 season, Jupiler pro league average attendance was 11,759 spectators while Bundesliga (best average in Europe) was 44,101 spectators and Eredevisie 18,805 spectators.

Regarding the stadium capacity, Jupiler Pro League can welcome 17,224 spectators in average and manage to fill 68% of available seats.

string: The “Ligue 1” is regulated by an independent commission, the DNCG (Direction Nationale du Contrôle de Gestion). This commission is in charge to validate the financial accounts (forecasts and statements) and legal statutes of all French professional clubs. The ultimate objective is to maintain fairness by controlling the clubs and have the guarantee that all the clubs engaged in French competition will be able to finish the season (i.e economically speaking). DNCG can use various range of decision to meet their objectives (fine, point reduction, payroll frame, relegation…).

The performance of French clubs in UEFA competitions has been poor those last years. In turn, France stands now fifth behind Italy and in front of Portugal (the UFEA season is not finished yet). Thus club finishing 3rd of the Ligue 1 has to play 2 rounds instead of 1 previously to qualify to the UEFA Champions League group stage. They have started the 2019/20 season with 58,498 points (5th rank) to be compared with Germany 71,927 points (4th rank) and Russia 50,549 (6th rank).

Focus on French Direction nationale du contrôle de gestion “DNCG” regulations:

In compliance with the dispositions of article L 132-2 of “code du sport”, by-laws and regulation of Fédération Française de Football “FFF” (French FA) and the convention between the FFF and the Ligue Professionelle de Football “LFP”, it is established a DNCG as an independent body in charge of controlling and monitoring legal and financial activities of affiliated clubs and ensure compliance with UEFA and national regulations. The commission in charge of controlling and auditing professional clubs is composed of 16 members nominated by different Football entities (FFF, LFP etc).  Clubs have to comply with DNCG requirements to fulfill its mission and notably regarding the reporting of documents and the respect of LFP / FFF accounting principles. The priority mission of DNCG is to ensure the continuity of operations of regulated clubs and prevent insolvency by taking the appropriated measures. It is an a priori control. It also assesses clubs participating to UEFA competitions delivering a certificate of compliance of UEFA licensing regulations.

Reporting obligations of clubs include principally:

  • To comply with FFF / LFP accounting principles
  • To account for all operations
  • To collaborate with any investigation from Football bodies and provide all requested pieces of legal, financial or accounting information
  • To produce before the 15th of March intermediary set of accounts audited for 31/12 closing and a statement of overdue debts, if applicable toward employees, tax and social administrations and football clubs regarding the trading of players activity
  • To produce before the 15th of May to prepare the audition the forecasted financial statements of the current season and the next one. A three year stress case scenario
  • To provide at the latest the day of the audition a statement letter mentioning any material change versus documents provided on 15th of May
  • When the licence has been granted the clubs remains with the obligation to inform the DNCG of any material event that could threaten the club capacity to continue operations during the period for which the licence has been granted
  • To provide at the latest on 30th of September the audited financial accounts of the previous season closing June 30th
  • To produce at the latest on 15th of November, the update of the forecast of financial accounts for the current season

The DNCG can take financial sanctions against clubs that won’t respect the reporting requirements. The DNCG will audit and assess the legal and financial situations and can apply the following scope of actions:

  • Full or partial transfer ban
  • Cap on payroll and transfers spending
  • Cap on the number of transfers of players
  • Relegation
  • Ban on promotion
  • Exclusion from competitions
  • Consultative opinion to LFP on the registration of players
  • Consultative opinion to UEFA on the granting of a regulated club UEFA licence
  • Publication of clubs accounts in compliance with the conditions decided by LFP
  • Apply all dispositions specified in by-laws and regulations of FFF and LFP

 

Following the “Covid 19” situation, the DNCG sent to all the clubs a letter on May 11th to give some guidelines regarding the next financial examinations (estimated 30/06/2020 and forecast 30/06/2021). The commission will have a special look on the following points:

  • Reliability and strength of the cash plan showing prudence in the disbursement.
  • Using the broadcasting rights increase to consolidate equity, invest in infrastructures, decrease indebtness. The commission precise that the clubs should not allocate all this resource increase in the payroll.

Mediapro has spent € 780 mm to acquire lots 1, 2 and 4. It is a Spanish audiovisual company with a historical presence in La Liga and making its entrance into Ligue 1. Lot 3 was acquired by BeIN Sports for € 320 mm while lot 6 was acquired by Iliad.

Canal +, historical broadcaster of Ligue 1 since its foundation in 1984, did not acquire any lots but bought sub-licenses from BeIN sports (2 games per week) in a global distribution deal.

New programmation of matches:

  • One premium match on Saturdays at 9pm
  • Multiplex (4 matches) will occur on Sundays at 3pm vs Saturdays at 8pm currently. This will enhance attendance rates with new types of spectators (families, women, children)
  • One match on Sundays at 1 pm to benefit from a Prime Time in Asia
  • Ligue 2 matches will occur on Saturdays at 7pm vs Fridays at 8 pm currently to enhance attendance rates. No conflict with Ligue 1 programmation

New commercialization offers:

  • Sub-licenses enabling broadcasters to sell matches to other broadcasters
  • Double sequence for broadcasters that will first choose its time slots then its matches
  • 7 lots to attract new actors

 

Joe Media SL, the holding company and ultimate consolidating entity of Mediapro activities, has been recently (April 2020) downgraded by Moody’s from B1 to B3 (speculative, high credit risk). This downgrade is led by weaker operating performances than expected in 2019, liquidity pressure with upcoming cash needs and 2020 outlook affected by the Coronavirus outbreak.

Ligue 1 proceeds on the same basis as most of its European peers (Italy, England or Spain): 20 clubs take part into Ligue 1 and 2 of them are relegated (a 3rd team will play a play off game against a 2nd division team) each year. The relegation risk in Ligue 1 (12,5%) is in line with the Big 8 average (13.4%). The predictability of the championship is in the European standards: (1) the correlation between trading expenses and ranking in the last 3 seasons is the same as the average of the other leagues and (2) with 33 different clubs playing the championship in the last 10 years, Ligue 1 lies in the industry standards.

Stadium capacity has increased during the last decade. This results from the investments in the stadiums that hosted Euro 2016. Stadium renovations have also improved matchday experience and revenues with enhanced business seats and catering offers.

The average number of spectators in the stadium is stable (22 529 for the season 2019-2020).

In regard of new match programmation from 2020 – 21 combined with 2019 World Cup Winner title and the arrival of new star players, attendance is expected to increase over the next few years.

Trading has been a balanced activity for Ligue 1 over the past years. However, this situation might change in the future. Previously main buyers like Olympique Lyonnais (OL), Olympique de Marseille (OM) or Lille Olympique Sporting Club (LOSC) used to partially buy players from other French clubs. On the contrary, the new mercato main players, Paris Saint Germain (PSG) and Monaco (ASM), have a much more international strategy regarding their purchases. During the last few years, a new type of investor arrived in France with a global trading strategy (LOSC, Monaco, Bordeaux…).

string: On the European scale, FA PL is one of the most competitive championships. If we take into consideration the last 5 years, given the good result of clubs such as Manchester United, Chelsea or Arsenal in the European competitions (in particular UEFA Champions League), FA PL lies just behind Liga BBVA (72.25 vs. 76.45) and far better than the Big 8 average (56.2). 2011/2012 was below expectations. Despite Chelsea winning UEFA Champions League last year, England’s UEFA index for the 2011/2012 season (15.25) is below the Spanish one (20.86) but still above the Big 8 average (14). Sportive results being closely tied to revenues, the competitiveness of FA PL is driven by the considerable resources that are available to the clubs. FA PL is the only league where all the clubs that take part in the championship have revenues above 50M€. This situation will be strengthened with the new TV deal that will allocate new resources to every clubs.

For long the FA PL tops the European Leagues in term of revenue but has been characterized by poor profitability. The 2013/14 marked a shift as it is the first time since 1999 that the FA PL clubs recorded a profit in aggregate. It has been driven by increasing commercial revenue from clubs, new broadcasting deal and control of wages. In 2013/14 the FA PL clubs recorded € 4.1bn in revenue before trading of players which is almost double of the Bundesliga (18 clubs) with € 2.3bn in revenue and far higher than Spanish Liga BBVA (€ 1.9bn), Italian Série A (€1.9bn), and French Ligue 1 (€ 1.5bn). Before trading FA PL recorded an operating profit of € 27 MM in 2013/14 vs an operating loss of € 509 MM in 2012/13. In 2013/14 it is the only League in the top 5 with the Liga BBVA (operating profit of € 19 MM) to report positive operating result. Bundesliga reported an operating loss before trading of players of € 132 MM, Ligue 1 of € 351 MM and Série A of € 583 MM.

FA Premier League is currently broadcasted in 212 countries over the world by more than 80 broadcasters. Broadcasting remains the most important revenue stream for all of the big 5 leagues, with the exception of the German Bundesliga. In 2015, the FA sold domestic TV rights for the 2016 – 19 period for a record £ 5.14 bn to BSkyB and BT. Overseas TV rights have so far followed the same trend and are being negociated for the 2016–19 period.

In 2017 – 18, FA PL clubs shared £ 2.4 billion net TV rights which is by far the highest amount in all European leagues for broadcasting. 

The allocation of TV right revenues is equitable as it is split in 3 ways : (1) 50% “equal share”, (2) 25% dependent on how many times a club was on TV (facility fees) and (3) 25% dependent on where a club finished in the table (merit payment). Thanks to this allocation, Premier League is the most equitable Championship among the main European leagues (ratio top to bottom of 1.6).

New domestic TV rights cycle (2019 – 22) were sold in 2018 for £ 4.464 billion (with 2 live packages still to be sold) indicate a slight decrease vs current cycle (£ 5.14 billion) and therefore, a saturation point of the market.

Sky Sports and BT Sport will continue to screen live Premier League football.

Sky will again show the vast majority of live games after securing the rights to four of the packages that were put up for auction by the Premier League for a total price of £ 3.58 billion. 

BT has so far bought the rights to only one of the available packages, comprising 32 games per season on a Saturday lunchtime, for a total pricie of £ 885 mm.

UEFA Club Licensing and Financial Fair Play

Clubs participating in the Champions League and Europa League competitions are subject to the UEFA Club Licensing and Financial Fair Play regulations ("FFP regulations"). This include two main legislations:

  1. No overdue payables: Since 2010, clubs that are qualified for UEFA competitions have to prove they have no overdue payables towards other clubs, their players and social/tax authorities throughout the season.
  2. Break-even requirement: Since 2013, clubs are required to balance their spending with their revenues and restricts clubs from accumulating debt. This assessment is made by the independent Club Financial Control Body analyzing each season three years’ worth of club financial figures. To be exact, clubs can spend up to € 5 mm more than they earn per assessment period (3 years). If the club owner(s) or a related party covers losses, this limit can go up to € 45 mm for assessment periods 2013 – 14 and 2014 – 15 and € 30 mm for assessment periods from 2015 – 16. To promote investment in stadiums, training facilities, youth development and women’s football all costs are excluded from the break-even calculation.

Non-compliance with the regulations does not mean that a club will be excluded automatically, but there will be no exceptions. Depending on various factors (e.g. the trend of the break-even result) different disciplinary measures may be imposed against a club. There is a catalogue of measures:

  1. Warning
  2. Reprimand
  3. Fine
  4. Deduction of points
  5. Withholding of revenues from a UEFA competition
  6. Prohibition on registering new players in UEFA competitions
  7. Restriction on the number of players that a club may register for participation in UEFA competitions, including a financial limit on the overall aggregate cost of the employee benefits expenses of players registered on the A-list for the purposes of UEFA club competitions
  8. Disqualification from competitions in progress and/or exclusion from future competitions
  9. Withdrawal of a title or award

Premier League Profitability and Sustainability regulations

The Premier League has also introduced regulations that aim to promote sustainability through profitability.

  1. Break-even requirement: A break-even test similar to the one practiced in UEFA Financial Fair Play regulations is being implemented.
  2. Short-Term Cost Controls: Commenced in 2013 – 14: All PL teams are essentially required to limit annual increases in player wage costs, compared to 2012 – 13 season, to £ 12 mm in contract year 2015 – 2016, £ 19 mm in 2016 – 17, £ 26 mm in 2017 – 18, and £ 33 mm in 2018 – 19. An exception can arise if the exceed is funded by increases in such team's revenue compared to 2012/13, excluding Premier League broadcasting revenue.

Potential sanctions for non-compliance with the profitability and sustainability regulations include significant fines, player transfer restrictions and Premier League points deduction.

Even though the German Bundesliga has taken over the top spot since it has renovated and expanded capacity of its stadium for the 2006 World Cup, match day income is the second highest revenue stream for FA PL clubs. Every FA PL club has its own stadium. Stadiums have a capacity of 38,365 seats in average (vs. 32,612 in average for the 6 main European championships and 45,251 for Bundesliga, number one in this category). In 2013/14 the average FA PL attendance has been 36,370 which is the second highest after the German Bundesliga (43,499) and before the Spanish Liga BBVA (26,955), Italian Série A (23,011) and French Ligue 1 (20,953). Liverpool FC operates at an average attendance of 45,000 which is above the average of the FA PL.

This summer, one third of the total transfer activity in the Big 8 leagues came from England (the trading volume in England reached 930.8M€). Therefore the global trading market heavily relies on England. In 2012/2013, new players arrive in FA PL for record amount (eg. Hazard from Lille to Chelsea for 40M€) or leave their clubs for another Premier League club (eg. Van Persie from Arsenal to Manchester United). Trading activity is one of the main weaknesses of FA PL since it is an area where it shows a structural deficit. In 2012/2013 (summer transfer period only), trading activities resulted in a record deficit of 328.5M€ far above the runner up, Bundesliga with a 102.8M€ deficit.

Even though compared to Germans English people are less involved in Football - registered players only represent 2.5% of the population vs. 7.7% in Germany – FA Premier League remains the most popular Championship in the world. In terms of revenues, FA PL is by far above its European peers, especially “the Big 8” (i.e. German Bundesliga, French Ligue 1, Italian Lega Calcio, Spanish Liga BBVA, Portuguese Super Liga, Dutch Eredive, Belgium Jupiler Pro League and FA PL). This has historically enables clubs within the FA PL to attract some of the world’s best footballers and to build competitive squads on a European scale.

string: The Spanish clubs dominate UEFA competitions for the past years. Indeed in UEFA Europa League of the past 10 editions, Spanish clubs won 6 editions (Atletico Madrid three times and FC Sevilla three times). In UEFA Champions League the Spanish clubs won 5 of the past 6 editions (FC Barcelona once and Real Madrid 4 times). Spain dominates UEFA ranking occupying the first rank with 103,569 points (England is second with 85,462 points).

La Liga financial structure has benefited from the reinforcement of its economic control with notably the following rules:

  1. Art. 20: Similarly as in UEFA Financial Fair Play “FFP”, clubs can spend up to € 30 mm more than they earn per 3-year assessment period. Net result is here defined as : net result before tax + amortization of tangible assets + revenues from young teams (“Cantera”)
  2. Art. 22: Payroll cost of the 1st team should not exceed 70% of total revenues, trading included.
  3. Art. 23: The ratio between net debt and total revenues should not exceed 1 (net debt = total financial and trading debt – trading receivables and cash).

Historically, La Liga stands apart from its major European rivals as it used to sell their TV rights on an individual basis, rather than a collective bargaining process through the League “LFP”. Therefore, the disparity between the “Big 2”, Real Madrid and FC Barcelona, and the rest of the League, used to be a structural trend in La Liga.

Consequently, Spanish government and clubs agreed to switch to a collective bargaining model from 2015 – 16 in which the LFP negotiates the sale of broadcasting rights and other commercial rights and then redistribute them to clubs. It has been ratified by Royal decree 5 / 2015 in April, 2015 with the following most relevant items:

  • Revenues to be shared among clubs affiliated to LFP (1st and 2nd division);
  • 90% of revenue to be distributed to 1st division clubs and 10% to 2nd division clubs;
  • Regarding 1st division, distribution follows a 50% / 25% / 25% pattern based on:
    • 50% equally distributed among clubs;
    • 25% based on past 5 years ranking with a ponderation between seasons and for which the first club receives 17% share and the last 0.25% share;
    • 25% based on social impact that still need to be defined by the LFP within the framework defined by the Royal decree stating that one third should be based on the number of ticket sales and two third based on the club participation to the LFP revenue generation in broadcasting and commercial rights. No club can receive a share higher than 20% or lower than 2%.
    • In the last two criteria, the difference between the club which receives the most and the one which receives the less cannot be higher than 4.5x. If the total revenue exceeds € 1 billion this ratio should progressively linearly tend to 3.5x which is the maximum ratio for a revenue equal or higher than € 1.5 billion.

The collective bargaining has allowed the League to negotiate higher revenue that can have a substantial impact on smaller clubs while guaranteeing the same level of revenue for Real Madrid and FC Barcelona. 

Parachute payments in case of relegation will be of € 10 mm per relegated club.

string: Italian teams have appeared in 26 Champions League finals and have won 12 times the competition. No country has produced more finalists and only Spain has produced more winners. During last decade, results are still good with 3 wins (Inter Milan 2010 and Milan AC 2007 and 2003) same as Spain and England. However, since Inter Milan victory, following the poor performances of the Italian clubs in the UEFA European Competitions, Calcio UEFA’s 5-year index dropped from 3rd to 4th place, below Liga BBVA, Premier League and Bundesliga and above Portugal Superliga and French Ligue 1. Therefore Calcio has lost a group stage spot for the Champions League.

As last year, in term of revenue generation, the Premier League clearly tops the big 5 leagues with almost double revenue than the Bundesliga:

Source: DNCG, Bundesliga, CSD and Calcio reports. Premier League individual accounts aggregated by Sport Value (exchange rate 1.36 € = 1£).

Overall, payroll to revenue has remained relatively similar to last season’s. In line with revenue the Premier League spends the mosts in wages of players, staff and administration (payroll) including social security tax. Liga BBVA spends in 2014–15 slightly more on wages than Serie A but with a less effective cost management whereas Bundesliga remains a League with an historical strong track record in cost management. Note that the difference in social security expense is significant from one country to another. Indeed, French clubs will pay around 35% English clubs around 12% Spanish, German and Italian clubs around 3-4% only.

In terms of profitability:

  •  Serie A keeps registering losses on both levels with a very poor debt situation (6* superior to Bundesliga). High wages when compared with revenues and high dependence on broadcasting revenues are the two principal explanations.
  • Bundesliga’s profitability is solid and should improve over the next years with increasing tv rights to be expected with in parallel, a solid debt situation. it is the healthiest football league.
  • Ligue 1 profitability remains negative even though it improved compared to 2013–14. However, this poor cash generation is balanced by a low debt compared to Serie A or Premier League.
  • La Liga maintains a satisfying profitability with its two giants, Real Madrid and FC Barcelona (42 + 15 = € 57MM).
  • Premier League’s profitability has considerably decreased and operating profit even went negative not because of poorer revenue generation but poorer cost management.

Media rights are by far the main source of income for Serie A clubs (~ 60% of total revenue in average). Since 2010 – 11, the sale of broadcasting rights has been managed centrally and collectively by the national league, LNP. The main national broadcaster is Sky Italia. There are five elements that contribute to the overall deal :

Former deal ran from 2015 – 16 until 2017  –18. The 20 clubs of Série A received a net total of € 975 mm net every year from domestic broadcasting (Série A and Tim cup). Infront Sports et Média et MP & Silva werein charge to sell the rights domestically (Infront) and internationally (MP&Silva). Counting international TV rights, the 20 clubs of Série A received annually ~ € 1 billion (net value).

Source: Football Leagues – Net TV rights distributed to 1st division clubs

(*): Bundesliga 1.: 2017 – 18 estimates

During spring 2017, Série A launched an auction for 2018 – 21 TV rights cycle with an innovative commercialization offer. The objective was to achieve € 1 billion of domestic TV rights per season vs € 945 mm today (+6%).

Série A has implemented several tranches of auction according to different broadcasting media:

  • 2 lots (A and B) 248 matches in live per season broadcasted on TV, worth minimum € 200 mm each. Lot A regards 8 teams, of which Juventus, AC Milan, Inter Milan, and Napoli. Lot B is reserved to Italian operators and regards the 12 other teams
  • 2 lots (C1 and C2) for internet operators, e.g. Amazon or Facebook, worth € 100 mm each.
  • Lot D for Over-The-Top (OTT) operators, e.g. DAZN, for 324 matches per season, including 132 exclusive matches and the Roma Derby, worth minimum € 400 mm

Série A would also implement 3 new time windows to have 8 time windows vs 5 today. This would  notably allow a better commercialization of its international TV rights.

On 13 June 2018, Lega Série A have sold TV rights for the seasons 2018 – 19, 2019 – 20 and 2020 – 21 to Sky and Perform Group for € 973 mm fixed and € 150 mm maximum additional payment (variable).

Juventus and Udinese are the only club in Italy to own its stadium. Since Italy’s 2016 UEFA Euro bid was unsuccessful, no plans have been announced to expand or build stadiums. Most of the stadiums in Italy are old and this poor level of infrastructure is the main obstacle to Italian Football economic development as of today. Contrary to most other leagues, some clubs - even the most prestigious – have to share their grounds (e.g. in Milan or Rome). The Italian clubs suffer from poor infrastructures with old stadiums that do not allow to monetize the full potential of their brand and activity during matchdays and out of matchdays notably as regard to hospitalities offered to VIPs and commercial partners.

In 2015-16 the average attendance in Série A has been 22 162 that is to be compared with an average attendance for the same period of 36 461 in the English Premier League, 43 300 in the German Bundesliga, 28 568 in the Spanish la Liga and 20 896 in the French Ligue 1.

Historically Italy has been a net importer of players and Calcio clubs have been able to attract the best players in the world. With the current economic situation it remains a net importer of players but to a lesser extent. Italy is still producing excellent players – World Cup winner in 2006 and runner up in this summer’s European Championship is testament – but now clubs are being forced to sell some of their best players to limit their losses.

An important and unique Lega Calcio’s specificity is that domestic transactions are settled through LNP which acts as a clearing house. This aims at limiting the amount of overdue payables among Calcio clubs and is therefore a key risk mitigant which does not exist anywhere else in Europe. Indeed as described previously every deficit position has to be covered with a strong collateral.

With 31M fans and 1.2M registered players, football is by far the most popular sport in Italy. This fame has been driven by the sportive results of the Italian National Team (finalist of the EURO 2012, 4 times World Champion) and of prestigious Italian clubs such as Milan AC, Inter Milan, Juventus and AS Roma (the “G4”). However Italian football has crossed a severe crisis for the past 5 years. Many extra sportive incidents such as the Juventus’ “drug-trial” in 2004, the Calciopoli scandal of 2006, fan violence or the Calcio scommesse (match fixing) scandal, have had severely impacted the First Italian Division (“Lega Calcio”, “Calcio” or “Serie A”) which has entered a steady decline.

string: In comparison to the “Big 5” (Bundesliga, Ligue 1, Lega Calcio, Liga BBV and Premier League) Süper Lig lies far behind in a number of key financial indicators. In terms of revenues, Süper Lig, with an average of €25m as average total revenues per club, lies clearly in the second tier in Europe, closer from the Dutch league (€24m) or the Portuguese league (€19m) than from French one (€57m in average for Ligue 1 clubs). Despite steady growth in 2010, in FY2011 Turkish club average revenue has been dropping by 14%. Furthermore, Süper Lig faces many financial imbalances. Main issues concern indebtedness, solvability and profitability. Majority of Turkish clubs have liabilities in excess of assets and wage to turnover ratio reaches in average 72%.3 of the 20 largest operating losses in Europe were reported by Turkish clubs in FY2010. Relevant examples of this situation are Besiktas and Bursaspor which were banned by UEFA from playing European competitions for violating "financial fair play" regulations. UEFA judged that the clubs breached financial licensing rules which require that all salaries and transfer fees are paid.

In terms of broadcasting rights, the Turkish Süper Lig is the sixth most valuable championship in Europe. With €351m per year, it is in an intermediary position in between the Big 5 and the rest of Europe since it is the only league receiving less than €500m per year and more than €100m per year. The allocation system is - for the moment - to the benefit of the "Big 3". The current Turkish broadcasting deal with telecommunication company Digiturk distributes only 35 percent of total income equally, while 45 percent is distributed based on performance and 10 percent to the Turkish Football Federation.  The drawback is the increasing gap between top clubs and the rest of the league. This kind of allocation mechanism is in the short term advantageous to top Turkish clubs, but reduce the competitive balance within the league and does not benefit Turkish football in the long run. Turkish sharing system is expected to get in line with the English one starting from 2014/2015 season ensuring a better allocation to small clubs.

Information on domestic broadcaster: Turkey's largest satellite television provider Digiturk was seized by Ankara's Savings Deposit Insurance Fund (TMSF). Its mother company, Çukurova Holding, owed extensive debts to TMSF that could not be paid. TMSF acquired Çukurova's 54% stake in Digiturk, the remainder of the company is owned by Rhode Island-based Providence Equity Partners. This seizure should not threaten the payments related to the Süper Lig broadcasting rights. Moreover, Turkey's Competition Board (RK) has launched an investigation into a deal between the Turkish Football Federation (TFF) and Turkish broadcaster Digiturk on broadcasting rights for TFF's Süper League games. The deal has been extended for two more years without the approval of the RK. The alleged extension would hamper fair competition, and therefore deeper investigations are currently conducted.

As mentioned previously, Süper Lig is characterized by the hegemony of the 3 major clubs of Istanbul (50 titles for the “Big 3” in 57 seasons). There are 18 clubs competing in the Süper Lig. At the end of each season, the 3 lowest placed teams are relegated. On the European level, Süper Lig competiveness has been stagnating since the 2006/2007 season. Süper Lig has 2 berths for the Champions League, (only one direct qualification to the group stage) and 3 berths for Europa League. It has been ranking between the 10th and the 11th best leagues in Europe in the past 6 years with a 5 year UEFA index which has stayed at 34, still far from Ukraine and Netherland (45 in 2011/2012).

Turkey tends to have higher average ticket prices but also lower attendances compared to its European peers (€35 match day income per attendee according to UEFA in FY2010 with an average attendance of 10,000 per game).  Lack of support for local teams as well as repetitive hooliganism issues explain Süper Lig low attendance (10,000 in average far from Ligue 1 average 18,869). Given the predominance of Istanbul’s clubs over Süper Lig, it has become typical for fans to support any of these teams. The Big 3 have the highest average attendance ratings every season in Turkey while the other teams lack support from the locals and suffer from poor attendance. The Big 3 also have the biggest stadiums in Turkey.

Hooliganism is still a burning issue in Turkey driven by the fierce rivalry among the Big 3. Turkey's parliament has approved strict legislation aimed at fighting against hooliganism (6 years in prison for fans who dismantle seats, 2 years in prison for fans who chant racial slurs and obscenities) but still hooliganism issues are far from being eradicated, and incidents regularly broke out during derby.

In terms of trading, the situation is heterogeneous. The 2 major Turkish clubs ranks among the top 50 net spenders, (14th and 17th) spending an estimated €129m and €99m between 2000 and 2010. The playing time of locally trained players have been decreasing in Turkish Süper Lig, in particular within the major clubs (50.9% of players were expatriates in 2011/2012, i.e. 4th worst in Europe). Payables related to transfer activities could become a threat to the financial health since Turkish clubs reported the largest net payables balance among major European leagues, equivalent to 20% of annual revenue in FY2010.

The Turkish championship is characterized by the dominance of the “Big 3”, Fenerbahçe, Besiktas and Galatasaray. The 3 most powerful clubs in Turkey all 3 based in Istanbul are far ahead from the other competitors in terms of revenues, fan base, infrastructures or sport records. With the exception of Trabzonspor (6 times) and Bursaspor (1), only those 3 clubs have won the Turksih First Division (Süper Lig): Besiktas (13) Fenerbahçe (18) and Galatasaray (19). These 3 clubs generally end up sharing the top positions, qualifying for UEFA cups.

Recent match fixing allegation scandal: Lack of transparency is a major issue in Turkish football and concern Turkey's top two association football divisions, the Süper Lig and First League. Fenerbahçe officials are under suspicion of fixing matches to help win the 2010/2011 title. Fenerbahçe was excluded from last season’s Champions League after UEFA pressured the Turkish Football Federation to withdraw the club’s entry days before the group-stage draw. Trabzonspor officials are also implicated in the criminal probe, though UEFA permitted the club to take Fenerbahçe’s Champions League place last season. Besiktas officials have also been charged with helping fix matches. There are ongoing investigation about match fixing, incentive premium, bribery, establishing a criminal organization, organized crime, extortion, threat and intimidation. On July 2, 2012, Turkish State Court sentenced the chairman of the Turkish club Fenerbahçe, Aziz Yildirim, to 3 years and 9 months for match-fixing and 2 years and 6 months for forming an illegal organization, but released him on bail pending an appeal. Galatasaray has not been incriminated so far.

The Portuguese championship is characterized by the dominance of the “Big 3”, i.e. the 3 most powerful clubs in Portugal. With the exception of Belenenses in 1945/1946 and Boavista in 2000/2001, only 3 clubs have won the Portuguese First Division (Superiga, or Liga Sagres): SL Benfica (35 times), FC Porto (27) and Sporting Clube de Portugal - “Sporting CP” - (18). These 3 clubs generally end up sharing the top 3 positions, qualifying for UEFA cups. 

The first division is large being composed of 18 clubs for a relatively small country (10.5 millions). All other clubs have very few revenues and visibility in Europe or globally which weakens the championship and its competitiveness. TV rights are negociated individually and are very low apart from the big 3. There is for the top 3 clubs the possibility as it happens in Spain of a future collective negociation of TV rights through the league. All clubs in Portugal face severe financial difficultie within a difficult economic environment in the country.
